This paper deals with network models and their properties, specifically preferential attachment models and their lack of higher-order clustering. This suggests that the paper could belong to the Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) category. Additionally, the paper discusses power-law distributions, which are commonly studied in the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DM) category. The paper also mentions eigenvalue spectra, which are related to linear algebra and graph theory, making the Graph Theory (cs.GT) category a possibility. The paper's focus on network sampling and robustness could also place it in the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NE) or Systems and Control (cs.SY) categories. Overall, the most likely categories are cs.SI, cs.DM, cs.NE, cs.SD, and cs.GT.
